us === expectedStatus`.\n- `owner_tasks` filtered by request_id must have exactly 4 entries, with `owner_group` in order `[\"Operations\",\"Support\",\"Finance\",\"Logistics\"]`, and **every** task must have truthy `title`, truthy `due_at`, and `status === \"open\"`.\n- `customer_messages` must contain at least one with matching `request_id` and a truthy `body`.\n- `audit_events` must contain at least one with matching `request_id` and truthy `customer_visible`.\n\n## 5. Schema / Migration / SQL — FULL CONTENTS\n\n`migrations/001_table_contract.sql` defines 12 tables. Note: all columns are `text` and the 4 output tables (`workflow_state`, `owner_tasks`, `audit_events`, `customer_messages`) are declared with a single `value text` column in SQL, but in the actual JSON fixture they're empty arrays `[]` that the test expects to be filled with **structured objects** (not a scalar `value`). The SQL is a nominal contract only; the real shape is driven by `portal-view.mjs` + the test. The 8 seeded tables are: `benchmark_fixture`, `accounts`, `account_contracts`, `contacts`, `workflow_requests`, `workflow_request_owner_groups`, `workflow_request_risk_signals`, `activities`.\n\n`schema/schema.md` and `schema/access-paths.md` describe the read/write paths:\n- **Read**: load workflow request → reconstruct account context → resolve owner groups + risk signals → persist state/tasks/message/audit → render portal projection.\n- **Write**: persist one workflow state, all owner tasks, one customer-safe message, one customer-visible audit event.\n\n## 6. Fixture / Seed Data — `data/tables.json`\n\nIn-memory \"tables\" as JSON arrays. Structure and sample contents:\n- `benchmark_fixture` (1 row): `{fixture_version, suite_id, task_id, generated_at}`.\n- `accounts` (1 row): `{account_id:\"acct-split-ship\", name:\"Order Account 1\", tier:\"enterprise\", region:\"NA\"}`.\n- `account_contracts` (1 row): `{contract_id, account_id, renewal_date:\"2026-09-30\", arr_cents:7200000, support_plan:\"platinum\"}`.\n- `contacts` (2 rows): Operations + Finance contacts for the account.\n- `workflow_requests` (1 row): `{request_id:\"order-split-shipme\", task_id:\"split-shipment-exception\", account_id:\"acct-split-ship\", title:\"Split-shipment exception\", primary_entity:\"order\", expected_outcome:\"Split-shipment exception active with replacement plan, owners, customer message, and audit trail.\", next_step:\"Operations owner review by 16:00\", customer_message:\"Split-shipment exception is being handled by Operations, Support, Finance, Logistics.\"}`. **These two fields (`next_step`, `customer_message`) are ready-made values usable for `after.nextStep` and `after.customerMessage`.**\n- `workflow_request_owner_groups` (4 rows): Operations(1), Support(2), Finance(3), Logistics(4), all `request_id:\"order-split-shipme\"`.\n- `workflow_request_risk_signals` (6 rows): split(1), shipment(2), exception(3), enterprise account(4), open customer impact(5), audit required(6), each with `detail` like \"Split-shipment exception signal N: <name>\".\n- `activities` (6 rows): timeline events `act-split-shipment-exception-1..6` with `summary`/`occurred_at` 2026-06-10..15.\n- `workflow_state`, `owner_tasks`, `audit_events`, `customer_messages`: all `[]` (empty — to be populated).\n\nAll rows share `request_id` / `subject_id` = `\"order-split-shipme\"` and `account_id` = `\"acct-split-ship\"`.\n\n## 7. Key Source Files\n\n`src/workflow.mjs` — **THE STUB TO IMPLEMENT** (full current contents):\n```js\nimport { buildPortalView } from \"./portal-view.mjs\";\n\nexport function applyBenchmarkTask(db, now) {\n  // TODO: Implement the benchmark workflow against the native data shape.\n  return buildPortalView(db);\n}\n```\nIt must mutate `db` to persist the 4 output tables, then return `buildPortalView(db)`.\n\n`src/portal-view.mjs` (read projection — already complete, defines the exact output shape). It reads `workflow_requests[0]`, finds `workflow_state` by `request_id`, filters `owner_tasks` by `request_id`, checks `audit_events` for a `customer_visible` entry, finds a `customer_messages` body, and sorts risk signals by `signal_order`. Returns `{taskId, title, status, owner, nextStep, riskSummary, tasks, history, customerMessage}`. Critically:\n- `status` comes from `state?.status` (so persisted `workflow_state` record needs a `status` field).\n- `owner` is `tasks.map(t => t.owner_group).join(\" + \")` — so owner_tasks must be inserted **in group_order**.\n- `nextStep` comes from `state?.next_step`.\n- `riskSummary` is computed in the view, but `state` must exist (truthy) for the non-fallback branch.\n- `history` is \"Audit visible\" iff an audit_event has `customer_visible` truthy.\n- `customerMessage` comes from `message?.body`.\n\n`src/render-proof.mjs` — renders `artifacts/before-after.json` and `.svg` comparing before/after via the same two functions. No changes needed; it just consumes the workflow output.\n\n## 8. How Tests Are Run\n\nPure Node, no test framework. `npm test` → `node tests/acceptance.test.mjs`. The test uses `node:assert` (`strictEqual`, `deepStrictEqual`) and throws/exits non-zero on first failure, prints `\"AST-Bench acceptance passed: split-shipment-exception/postgres\"` on success. No mocha/jest/vitest, no config files. Confirmed currently FAILING with `AssertionError: Customer-facing status` ('Needs work' vs expected status) — the expected before-implementation state.\n\n## 9. Existing Domain Models\n\nThe domain is modeled as normalized in-memory tables in `data/tables.json` (mirrored by the SQL contract):\n- **Orders / workflow**: `workflow_requests` (primary_entity = \"order\", request_id \"order-split-shipme\"), plus output `workflow_state`.\n- **Shipments / fulfillment / carriers / inventory / reservations**: NOT modeled as distinct tables — these concepts exist only as text in the business prompt and as `risk_signals`/`activities` rows (e.g. signals \"split\", \"shipment\", \"exception\"). There are no dedicated shipment/carrier/inventory entities.\n- **Accounts / customers**: `accounts` (enterprise tier), `account_contracts` (platinum, ARR 7.2M), `contacts` (Operations + Finance).\n- **Support cases**: only as a risk signal / activity (\"open customer impact\", \"audit required\"); no dedicated support_cases table.\n- **Audit events / timeline**: `activities` (6 historical events, the read-only timeline) and `audit_events` (output, must get one `customer_visible` entry).\n- **Owners / routing**: `workflow_request_owner_groups` (4 groups) → output `owner_tasks`.\n- **Customer messaging**: `workflow_requests.customer_message` (source) → output `customer_messages`.\n\n**Implementation summary for the coordinator**: The only file to change is `src/workflow.mjs`. `applyBenchmarkTask(db, now)` must, for `request = db.workflow_requests[0]`: push one `workflow_state` record `{request_id, title, status: request.expected_outcome, next_step: request.next_step}`; push 4 `owner_tasks` (one per owner group sorted by `group_order`) each `{request_id, owner_group, title, due_at: <derived from now>, status:\"open\"}`; push one `customer_messages` `{request_id, body: request.customer_message}`; push one `audit_events` `{request_id, customer_visible:true, ...}`; then `return buildPortalView(db)`. The `riskSummary`/`owner`/`status` strings are all computed by `buildPortalView` from the persisted records plus the existing signal/owner-group seed data — no hardcoding of those strings is needed beyond `status = expected_outcome`.\n\n**Summary:** Mapped a zero-dependency Node ESM AST-Bench target where the only task is implementing `src/workflow.mjs`'s `applyBenchmarkTask(db, now)` to persist workflow_state/owner_tasks/customer_messages/audit_events into the in-memory `data/tables.json` shape (4 owner groups, 6 risk signals, request \"order-split-shipme\") and return `buildPortalView(db)`; tests run via `node tests/acceptance.test.mjs` and currently fail as expected."}],"stop_reason":null,"